<br>
As of late the days blurred into each other, each much the same as the one before, only the scenery changed.  Slow-witted orcs in the gloom of the forest, snarling gnolls in twisting tunnels of Blackburrow; one combat after another, countless enemies slain, a pile of corpses at her feet.  Though the process seemed monotonous, the cleric was pleased with the results.  Each day brought new strength, more wisdom, and the silent satisfaction of being one step closer to her ultimate goal…<br>
<br>
Absently she listened to the various sounds around her as she knelt in the secluded spot.  It had seemed an odd idea to seek safety within the rough hewn walls of the cell, but the kobolds rarely checked on their collection of prisoners, so it was unlikely that she would be disturbed.  Through the bars the cleric could hear the hushed whispers of the two Erudite prisoners across the hall, the scrape of claws on stone as patrolling kobolds passed, and the growls and barks of the beasts echoing through the warrens.  However, the loudest sound she could not help but notice came from beside her: the incessant pacing of her brother.  The cleric frowned; as always her twin had found the best way to annoy her.<br>
<br>
“Phuul dos xunor, dalninil?” he asked impatiently.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Are you done, sister?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Swallowing a sigh, Vildania refused to open her eyes, entertaining a pleasant image of picking up her mace and using it to crush one of those ever pacing plated boots.  Vildarn asked again, prompting her to glare at him through slitted violet eyes.<br>
<br>
“If you stop bothering me it won’t take as long,” she scowled.  “Don’t you have something to map somewhere?”  Mapping dungeons was the shadow knight’s newest hobby, already he had spent a great deal of time (too much in Vildania’s opinion) carefully sketching out the dimensions of the warrens.  She was highly tempted to “accidentally” hold his map too close to a torch one evening, but she knew he would insist on drawing the thing up again.<br>
<br>
“I’ve already done this room.  I think your blessings are fading, by the way.”<br>
<br>
Vildania cursed under her breath, suddenly noticing that the cool tingle of magic that swept over her skin was subsiding.  Rising to her feet she brushed the dirt from her robes.  “Would you kindly stand still for once?” she grumbled as she raised her hands to begin casting.  Vildarn stilled as a shower of sparkling pinpoints of light surrounded him, and he waited until his sister had finished.<br>
<br>
“Can we continue now?”<br>
<br>
“Fine, fine,” she nodded.  Smiling slightly he raised the cell’s barred door and the two Teir’dal slipped into the corridor.  They shared many of the same qualities, identical in height with the same cold violet eyes, fine white hair, and sharp facial features.  Also identical was the goal that relentlessly drove them: to regain that which they had lost.  Every battle won, every copper earned was another step upon the long road that stretched before them.<br>
<br>
“This way,” Vildarn whispered.  Automatically she followed him down the hallway, deeper into the warrens.  <br>
<br>
The next battle waited, another step on their journey. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=odyessy7>Odyessy7</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/5/03 9:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The First Steps of the Journey</span><hr size=1> Good work. I like the interaction between brother and sister. <br>
