<br>
“Tlu venorik dalninil,” Vildarn warned, swallowing a smirk.  Beside him his sister continued to curse, sullenly rubbing the top of her head.<br>
<br>
“Be silent, he says.  I’ll show you be silent,” she muttered under her breath.  Pulling her hand away she scowled at the blood that stained her fingers; a small patch of darkness matted her short-cropped white hair.  For a moment Vildania glared at the rock that had tumbled down from the ceiling and struck her, and she considered picking it up and throwing it at her brother.  Of course, it probably wouldn’t do much to that winged cooking pot he called a helmet…  “Where are we going?”<br>
<br>
“This way.” The shadow knight pointed towards a bend in the corridor.<br>
<br>
Vildania sighed.  “Could you be more specific?”<br>
<br>
“We’re going to the gorge of King Xorbb.”<br>
<br>
“Really.  This looks like another dungeon to me,” Vildania remarked, wrinkling her nose at their surroundings.  Recently the two Teir’dal had hunted in a series of glorified caves infested with vile creatures and filled with indescribable stench and filth.  The cleric wasn’t thrilled at the thought of exploring another one, as this seemed little different and the day already had an inauspicious start.<br>
<br>
“It is another dungeon.”  He chuckled as she shot him a poisonous glare in response.  “Don’t worry, this is a shortcut, we’re not staying,” Vildarn assured her.  With another sigh she wiped the blood onto the skirt of her robe and motioned for him to lead on.  The trip didn’t take long, a few twists and turns with only a few pauses to take care of goblins that took offense to their citadel being invaded by a pair of young dark elves.  At one point the twins watched in awe as a giant bipedal mushroom meandered past, seemingly oblivious to their presence as it bounced by.<br>
<br>
Emerging outside, the cleric peered at the new surroundings.  Craning her neck she looked up at the sheer rock walls that stretched towards the sky, noticing dark clouds that promised heavy rain.  A narrow path split before them, and Vildarn led the way down the left fork as the first drops started to fall.  Silence hung eerily in the air, punctuated only by the sounds of their boots as they walked and the occasional rumbles of thunder.<br>
<br>
Turning to the left again, the knight finally paused halfway up a small incline.  “We wait here,” he instructed.  “Things should wander by.”<br>
<br>
“What sort of things?” Vildania asked, raising an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Muddites, minotaurs, evil eyes.  Don’t touch the evil eyes.”<br>
<br>
She nodded in reply; the cleric had no idea what an evil eye was, but it sounded unpleasant.  Muddites, she soon discovered as her brother lured one up the hill, sounded exactly as the name led her to expect.  The stocky, ambulatory glob of mud resembled an earth elemental, only gooey.  Bits of mud flew everywhere as the twins struck with sword and mace, neither prepared for the experience of fighting a creature that had neither flesh to pierce nor bones to crush.  Vildania sputtered and nearly dropped her weapon as a handful of mud hit her square in the eyes, blinding her momentarily.  Thankfully Vildarn finished off the creature quickly, and then left his sister alone for several minutes as she tried to divide her attention between meditating and blinking the dirt out of her eyes.<br>
<br>
The minotaurs were something of a shock, as they were easily twice the twins’ size.  In their hunts the pair had fought many monsters, yet none of them had towered over the Teir’dal quite like this.  It made each fight against the beasts that much more anxious, and each victory that much more exhilarating.  As the day continued it fell into the familiar hunting pattern, alternating periods of combat and rest.  The rain fell intermittently throughout the afternoon, the clouds keeping the annoying sunlight at bay.  <br>
<br>
Vildania futilely brushed at her mud spattered robe as she rested on the small hillside, but the garment was hopelessly damp from the constant rain.  Glancing up she watched her brother as he stood next to her, scanning the pathways for their next potential prey.  Few things seemed to bother the knight while he was hunting, while every minor detail seemed to irritate the priestess.<br>
<br>
“Dalninuk, I’ve been thinking,” she said, interrupting the silence.  Her brother snorted derisively at the comment and she sighed.  “I’m serious.  I think we should find some companions to hunt with, or a guild of some sort.”<br>
<br>
“Why?”<br>
<br>
“Many reasons.  It would be helpful to us—“<br>
<br>
“We don’t need any help,” he interrupted, scowling.  Vildarn was proud and set in his ways; she had expected this reaction.<br>
<br>
“Well, while I do enjoy your stimulating conversation I wouldn’t mind having others to talk to once in awhile.  And no, Nogarl doesn’t count, sentences of three monosyllabic words don’t qualify as conversation,” Vildania countered.  They had been aiding a young troll, Nogarl, acquire armor and learn the layout of the area outside Neriak, as the shaman had promise to one day be a valuable asset to them in hunting.<br>
<br>
The shadow knight seemed to not be paying attention to her, peering intently at the path through the gorge.  Suddenly he reached down and grabbed hold of his sister’s arm, roughly dragging her to her feet and hauling her up the hill with him.  Before Vildania could protest he shushed her, leading her further away and then finally pushing her behind him once he stopped.  Confused she peeked around him to see what her brother watched so fixedly.  It took her mind a moment to recognize the floating shape as that of an enormous eye, a blinking yellow orb almost the size of a boulder that hovered ponderously above the ground.<br>
<br>
“What is that?” she whispered with a shudder.<br>
<br>
“That,” he answered quietly, “Is an evil eye, and I’ve no intention of angering one.  They can bend your mind as surely as an enchanter.”  Bobbing slightly the eye rolled as it scanned its surroundings and the two Teir’dal slipped into the shadows, hiding as best they could in the rain.  Eventually the evil eye moved, heading back into the gorge’s mazelike pathways, and the twins breathed a simultaneous sigh of relief.  <br>
<br>
“We can continue your discussion later, dalninil.  Now we should start for home,” Vildarn suggested, and she nodded.  Later was better than no, she reasoned silently as she followed him.  Later had potential.  Vildania could be patient; likely her brother would put off the conversation as long as he possibly could, and she could use that time to investigate things.  Yes, later definitely had potential… <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tayana>Tayana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/25/03 5:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The First Steps of the Journey</span><hr size=1> No rain spoiled the comforting gloom of the afternoon in Nektulos forest.  Here there were no blinding sunbeams, no strange voices constantly shouting in foreign tongues, no jostling, crowded streets.  Useful though the Plane of Knowledge might be, traveling through it grated on the cleric’s nerves.  This moment of quiet would be fleeting of course, and rightly so.  More battles waited, a long, winding road lined with blood and death that must be traveled.  Yet for now she had only her own thoughts to battle, and a river full of fish.<br>
<br>
Slender legs folded beneath her, the young Teir’dal flipped through a thin journal as she lounged on the riverbank, a nearly forgotten fishing pole propped up at her side.  Line after line of precise, tidy writing filled the book’s pages, and pensive violet eyes skimmed the information.  Her research had been enlightening, if not terribly encouraging.  It seemed many guilds and houses sought only those with at least fifty seasons of training; Vildania mentally filed their names away for use in a few years.  Fifty felt very far away indeed…<br>
<br>
An insistent tug on the line of the fishing pole reminded the cleric of why she’d ventured into Nektulos this day, and dropping her journal she picked the pole up, concentrating on reeling the fish in.  A piranha swam close to the struggling fish, considering snatching the quick meal, but then it wisely continued on its way—the last piranha that had gotten greedy ended up flash fried in an explosion of magical sparkles.  With a triumphant grin the cleric yanked her prize free of the water and quickly went about adding it to her collection of previous victims.  The fish served two purposes: first it was necessary for the fish wine she had been attempting to brew (but refused to drink, as in her opinion fish should never be a beverage.)  Secondly, her brother wanted it for his latest cooking attempt.  This time Vildarn was intent on perfecting a soup of some sort.  Vildania wasn’t going to argue; at least he was no longer pestering her with his mysterious sandwiches containing meat of undisclosed origins.  Once she had been certain she spied a rat tail dangling from between the two pieces of bread and had nearly gotten ill on the spot.  <br>
<br>
Wrinkling her nose in disgust, Vildania baited the hook and cast her line once again.  Picking up her journal she reexamined her notes.  There were a few places she could apply to that might take her, one in particular that she often pondered.  More than once the cleric had considered approaching them and introducing herself, but always she felt too nervous.  Usually she let Vildarn do the talking, disastrous though it had been on occasion, but he still stubbornly held to the idea that they didn’t need help.  Setting the book aside she reached up and absently toyed with the ends of her short hair; when she had first acquired the robe her long locks had kept getting tangled in the high collar, and in a fit of annoyance Vildania had chopped them off.  Though she understood that the state of her hair in no way affected anything important, like her abilities as a priestess of Innoruuk, there was a tiny part of her that mourned that she looked like a boy.  It wasn’t helpful in overcoming her shyness, and she despised herself for that weakness.<br>
<br>
Vildania sighed.  Once she acquired a few more fish she would return home, there were enough for her to practice with and some leftover to distract Vildarn—she was anxious to avoid more sandwiches.  A cry of alarm from further down the river suddenly broke the quiet, followed by the sounds of desperate combat.  Leaping to her feet the cleric grabbed for her weapon and shield and rushed along the riverbank, heading towards the bridge.  As she neared Vildania knew that it was already too late; a figure in shining armor, long golden ponytail streaming behind, retreated along the road to the Commonlands astride a great white horse, a lone dragoon in pursuit.  With a sinking heart the cleric stepped onto the bridge, all too familiar with the sight that stretched before her.  Four guards, young warriors barely older than boys, lay scattered across the stone, their bodies battered and bloodied.  Kneeling next to the closest she checked for signs of life, knowing the gesture was futile; defending the bridge was near to a death sentence.<br>
<br>
Instantly the grief turned to anger.  How many times must she witness this scene?  Her kin being hunted for sport by wretched paleskins?  Vildania longed to return the favor, her hands ached to loose weapon and magic in revenge, to see them suffer as the Teir’dal suffered.  The hatred burned, a searing she gladly welcomed.  Soon, she promised herself silently.<br>
<br>
Glancing up she noted the dragoon’s return, his slumped shoulders indicating his defeat.  He looked to the cleric, still kneeling over one of his men, and she shook her head.  The dragoon sighed.<br>
<br>
“Koada’dal,” he explained simply.  Vildania scowled, unsurprised.<br>
<br>
“I’ll gather my things and return to Neriak to let them know what happened,” she offered.  Nodding his thanks, the dragoon turned away from her as Vildania stood, brushing herself off.  It never ended, she mused silently as she hurried back to her fishing spot.  Yet soon, Innoruuk willing, she and her brother would be able to better aid in the conflict, and that was a comforting thought indeed. <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;">Vildania, Priestess of Innoruuk</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tayana>Tayana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/3/03 6:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.ripway.com/2003-11/39539/fel_crouch.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The First Steps of the Journey</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">The Comedy of Errors;<br>
