<br>
A slight wind whistled through the tunnel, hot and dry as the sands that waited on either end.  Thankfully the cavern that opened up off the passage was safe from the blistering desert heat and blinding sun; the dim light of torches and campfires almost made it reminiscent of Neriak, except for the motley assortment of races that milled about.  This was one of the camps of the Wayfarers Brotherhood, an organization that seemed to concentrate on the pursuit of adventure above all else.  It was a concept that Vildania, a Teir’dal priestess of Hate, found unsettling.<br>
<br>
Arms folded across her chest the cleric glanced around uneasily, eyeing the humans and high elves with silent suspicion.  While she saw them often enough in passing through the Plane of Knowledge, she had never lingered this closely.  As she turned she caught the gaze of an armored man watching her with an expression that was certainly inappropriate, and she frowned at him.  Noticing his sister’s disapproval Vildarn followed her glare and scowled at the human.  Stepping in front of Vildania he blocked her from sight, leaving the offender to shrug and ogle a passing wood elf instead.<br>
<br>
“I don’t like this,” Vildania said quietly.  Nervously she fidgeted with the ends of her hair as she glowered at her twin.  “Why should we work with these people?”<br>
<br>
“Because they have access to riches and magic we would not otherwise be able to acquire.  Do you want our enemies to alone have that advantage?”<br>
<br>
“No,” she admitted sullenly.<br>
<br>
“Then play along,” Vildarn advised.  “Here, Nogarl’s arrived.  I’ll go find if they’ve a task for us so we can be on our way.”  The shadow knight headed off to speak with one of the Wayfarers, and Vildania turned to the troll that ambled up and loomed over her.  Nogarl was always easily spotted, a hulking tower of menace and muscle wrapped in armor of a particularly lurid green shade.<br>
<br>
“He’s going to be smug the rest of the evening,” she warned the shaman.<br>
<br>
“This new?” Nogarl countered, tilting his head slightly.<br>
<br>
“True,” Vildania chuckled.  While they waited the pair began casting their blessings on each other; the cleric and shaman complimented each other well, their combined magic keeping the trio strong and, most importantly, alive.  Finally Vildarn returned, looking content.  “Well?” she impatiently prompted her brother.<br>
<br>
“They want us to go kill an orc.  One named Hoghul Xut.”<br>
<br>
“That’s it?  What’s the catch?” the cleric asked, raising an eyebrow.  Surely it couldn’t be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> simple.<br>
<br>
“That’s it.  It’s only an orc, how hard can it be?” Vildarn shrugged.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>One Hour Later…</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Coughing, the cleric leaned against the pile of barrels and spat a mouthful of blood onto the floor.  A sharp ache spread throughout her torso; cracked ribs most likely, annoying yet not too dire.  This was unlike any lair they had previously encountered, and the orcs and goblins were very different than what they were used to.  Taller and more muscled, these foes were formidable; hitting one of these orcs was rather like hitting a tree or a brick wall and took great effort to fell.  The first few battles had come near to disastrous endings, due to the combination of an overzealous shadow knight and a handful of orc casters (said shadow knight ending up singed and eyebrowless as a result.)  Yet the trio pressed on, clearing room after room, hallway after hallway, adapting to these unfamiliar surroundings.<br>
<br>
“Crate moving,” Nogarl grunted.  The troll pointed to a wooden crate in the corner of the room that shook back and forth, creaking as it moved.  Raising an eyebrow Vildania turned to her brother, who was already advancing towards the crate.<br>
<br>
“Stand back, I’ll open it,” Vildarn ordered.  A few rooms before this they had opened a similar crate only to find a handful of stinging, biting insects, so the knight waited until his companions were out of harm’s way before prying open the lid in case a similar nasty surprise appeared.  As he tugged at the container it suddenly fell apart in his hands and a goblin leapt out.<br>
<br>
“You have saved me from that crate, I would have met an awful fate!  I was a slave but now I’m not, now I know I won’t get caught!  Please, oh please can I go with you?  I can help you make it through!  Tell me to follow and I will, fighting together will be a thrill!” the goblin exclaimed excitedly.  Confused, the three hunters peered at the escapee.<br>
<br>
“Alright, you can follow me,” Vildarn reluctantly instructed the creature.<br>
<br>
“Yay!  Hooray!  Today is the day we send those beasts away!” the slave cheered.  Vildania blinked incredulously at her brother.<br>
<br>
“Are you mad?  You can’t be serious, he’ll stab you in the back first chance he gets,” she protested.  “We ought to finish it off now before it gets us killed like one of your brainless skeleton pets.”<br>
<br>
The goblin whined piteously and shivered, and Vildarn shrugged.  “We can use it for bait.  If it dies, it dies.”  Sighing in defeat she waved at him to lead on, and they made their way into the next room.  The party continued as before, inching their way through the dungeon, leaving naught but corpses in their wake.  True to its word, the goblin slave fought as best it could in its weak, weaponless state and followed obediently as the shadow knight’s heels.  Finally it collapsed as they were making their way down a rough stone corridor, the goblin’s dying whisper barely audible over the worrisome wind that howled around the tunnel’s bend.<br>
<br>
“Fighting with you was so much fun, and now for me death has come…” the slave whined quietly.  Its eyes fell shut and it lay still, and after a few moments Nogarl poked it curiously with his spear.<br>
<br>
“Good,” the troll rumbled.  “Quiet now.”<br>
<br>
Vildarn chuckled, “I’d consider keeping some of these as slaves of our own, if there wasn’t that constant rhyming to put up with.”  He nudged the body to the side of the tunnel—no sense tripping over it later—and they resumed their hunt.  Immediately after rounding the bend they realized that this corridor was indeed different, ending not in another room or hall but opening out into something much larger.  With each step the howl of the wind grew louder, and now they could hear something else in it, an endless roar of some sort.  Vildarn cautiously scouted ahead while the other two hung back, waiting.  The party paused as they suddenly heard a distant shout carried on the wind.<br>
<br>
“We have received words of intruders!” a gruff voice barked.  “Stand your ground, men.  They’ll never cross the wind bridges alive!”<br>
<br>
“Wind bridges?” Vildania glanced up at Nogarl, who merely shrugged in reply.  Standing at the arch at the end of the hall, Vildarn motioned them forward.<br>
<br>
“Don’t look down,” he warned as they approached.  A pathway stretched out from the arch, wooden with ropes on either side, and off to the left, barely visible was the source of the roaring sound—a waterfall.<br>
<br>
“Why not?”  The cleric’s eyes reflexively fell as she asked and she immediately regretted it.  Her stomach spun as she spied the dizzying drop, a gloomy mist hiding the bottom, if there was one at all.  Wooden suspension bridges crisscrossed the nothing, linking together towers and other holes in the rock walls.  “No.  Absolutely not.  Nothing in this world is going to get me onto that,” Vildania warned, shaking her head and taking a few steadying steps backwards.<br>
<br>
“We have to keep going,” Vildarn insisted.<br>
<br>
“I am not trusting my life to some orc built bundle of sticks and thread!”<br>
<br>
“We’ll be fine.”<br>
<br>
“No!”<br>
<br>
With a sigh the shadow knight turned to Nogarl and raised an expectant eyebrow.  Before Vildania had a chance to react the troll picked her up and easily tossed her over his shoulder, as nonchalantly as though he were slinging his backpack.  “Much better,” Vildarn nodded.  He started across the bridge, both men ignoring the cleric’s colorful curses and threats and concentrating on their surroundings.  The view was quite spectacular, like nothing either had ever seen before, and both suspected that the end of their task must be near.<br>
<br>
Once the cursing had quieted Nogarl put Vildania down and she sullenly followed, glaring poisonously at her companions.  They encountered a few guards on the bridges but managed to quickly dispatch them, and finally they scrambled up one last bridge to stand in another stone archway.  A gloomy mist made it difficult to see into the room, but they were able to spot a large orc, more elaborately dressed than the others they had encountered.<br>
<br>
“That must be him, Hoghul Xut,” Vildarn whispered.  “I’ll get his attention.”<br>
<br>
“Wait, there may be others with him, we need a better view,” his sister protested.<br>
<br>
“We’ll be spotted and lose our surprise if we go any closer.”<br>
<br>
“It’s too dangerous.”<br>
<br>
“I’m willing to risk it,” he insisted.  Stepping forward he silenced any further arguments by casting a spell, seeking to engulf Hoghul in darkness.  Alerted to danger a horde of angry orcs suddenly spilled forth out of the mist and charged the trio of intruders.<br>
<br>
“RUN!” Nogarl shouted.<br>
<br>
They ran.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Even later…</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
“You!”  The troll poked a gnarled finger across the table at the Teir’dal sulking on the other side.  “No more rush in, slay tings!”<br>
<br>
“Yes, you’ve lost your leading privileges,” Vildania agreed, wincing as she sipped her wine.  They had retreated to the Maiden’s Fancy to regroup and drown their sorrows.  Another drink or two and she wouldn’t feel the bruises anymore, something she greatly looked forward to.  Deciding not to reply, the shadow knight instead beckoned for another drink, and they sat in silence again.<br>
<br>
“It’ll be better next time,” he finally spoke up.  “At least now we’ve a better idea of what to expect.”<br>
<br>
“I suppose,” Vildania shrugged.  After all, she thought, it couldn’t get much worse, could it?<br>
<br>
Could it?<br>
<br>
Sighing, she took a long drink.  Somehow she had the feeling this was going to be the start of a very long and painful series of adventures… <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tayana>Tayana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/13/03 3:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.ripway.com/2003-11/39539/fel_crouch.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The First Steps of the Journey</span><hr size=1> Another restless night had driven the cleric out of bed, nervous energy preventing sleep once again.  The past several days had been damnably boring.  Nogarl had gone off on some sort of spiritual retreat; the twins still weren’t sure what it was that their hunting companion was doing, all they had been able to clearly understand were the words “shaman,” “think,” and “hot.”  …They were fairly certain a great deal was lost in translation.  Without the third member of their trio Vildarn and Vildania found themselves with a great deal of free time and very little to fill it with, which was partially responsible for the cleric’s insomnia.  Part, but not all…<br>
<br>
For a time Vildania wandered the streets of Neriak, winding her way through quiet shadows as she tried to walk off her anxiety.  Eventually the girl admitted to herself that she would find no peace this night, and after collecting her brewing materials she settled herself in the Blind Fish and worked on honing her skills.  Annoying though it was this free time had been very helpful in advancing her knowledge of the trade.<br>
<br>
Hours later Vildania returned home, arms laden with bottles of her latest batch of alcoholic experiments.  Slowly she pulled the door shut behind her, careful not to unbalance herself and send her burden crashing to the floor.  With a relieved sigh she set the bottles down on the table, and then took a moment to dust herself off before crossing to the door to the other room.  Vildania paused in the doorway, scowling at the sight before her.  Empty brandy bottles littered the floor, one tucked in the crook of her brother’s arm as he slept in a tangled sprawl.  Apparently he’d helped himself to the stock she kept for sampling and study.  Again.<br>
<br>
Where is that meat cleaver he calls a sword, I’m going to behead him this time… she thought sourly, glancing around the dark room.  Though her hands itched to take up the weapon Vildania took a deep, calming breath.  She couldn’t kill her twin.  At least not today.  The cleric had plans for him today.  Instead of reaching for the sword, Vildania picked up a pitcher of water and proceeded to pour it over her sleeping brother’s head.<br>
<br>
Sputtering curses Vildarn sat up and glared at his sister, who watched him expressionlessly.  “We’re leaving in ten minutes,” she informed him.<br>
<br>
“I’m not going anywhere.”  He scowled down at his soggy blanket and pillow.  Shaking his head he sent a spray of droplets flying from the ends of his hair, and then groggily stumbled across the room and helped himself to his sister’s bed.  Vildania rolled her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Yes you are.  It’s the least you can do since you stole my brandy.  From now on I’m going to start storing some of my failed attempts here too, and I won’t heal you if you go blind from drinking one.”<br>
<br>
Vildarn cursed under his breath.  “Fine.  This better be good.”<br>
<br>
“Oh, I promise you’ll thank me for this one,” she assured.<br>
<br>
<br>
Side by side the twin Teir’dal crouched in the shadow of a tall tree, two pairs of violet eyes scanning the shoreline.  They had traveled through the filthy streets of Freeport, something neither had done before, and had been transported to the small, sunny island.  Vildania led silently, offering no explanation as to where they were going or why, though her eagerness was evident in the spring in her steps.<br>
<br>
“What are we looking for?” he whispered.  The cleric held up a hand in warning, and then pointed up the hillside.<br>
<br>
“There,” she murmured.  Leisurely walking down the hill was a female wood elf, oblivious to their presence.  Dark hair floated around her shoulders, framing a face with delicate features and soft blue eyes.  The shapely elf was clad in armor that revealed more pale skin than it protected, and the halberd she carried looked a bit rusty from unuse.  Vildania smiled.<br>
<br>
“It’s a Feir’dal,” the shadow knight frowned, slightly confused.  Often they came across wood elves in their travels, the tree huggers seemed to infest the Plane of Knowledge along with their high elf brethren.  Why was this one special?  <br>
<br>
“A Sister of Erollisi,” Vildania corrected.  Grinning, she raised her hands and began casting a spell, suddenly rooting the startled wood elf into place.  Realizing his sister’s intentions the shadow knight raised his heavy two handed sword and advanced.  Determinedly the girl stood her ground and faced off against the dark elf, but quickly fell to her knees after two mighty swings nearly split her in half.  A blow from the cleric’s viciously spiked club tore jagged furrows in the elf’s lovely face, and then Vildania grabbed her brother’s arm, stopping him from making the killing blow.<br>
<br>
“Wait, dalninuk.  Let her suffer a bit first,” she advised.  Blue eyes looked pleadingly up at the two Tier’dal, wordlessly begging for mercy.  Head tilted to the side, the cleric of Innoruuk let her gaze travel over the broken body at her feet, noting the contrast of bright blood against pale skin, listening to the gurgle of wheezing, struggled breath.  Vildania was certain she had never seen anything so beautiful.<br>
<br>
“Th… the Sisterhood of Erollisi… and the Champions of Faydark… shall… avenge my… d… death!” the wood elf promised, her words interspersed with rattling coughs.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps,” Vildarn nodded, “But not today.”  With a final slash he permanently silenced the Feir’dal, a slight spray of blood raining over the twins.  After a moment he turned to Vildania.  “Are there more of them here?”<br>
<br>
“Yes,” she smiled, “Many more.”  Licking her lips the cleric savored the taste of her enemy’s blood.  “Many more indeed…”<br>
<br>
“You were right,” the shadow knight grinned.  “I will thank you for this.” <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Vildania D'Varr, Priestess of Innoruuk</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showPrevMessage?topicID=1227.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showNextMessage?topicID=1227.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=6><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/classic/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.threadControl?topicID=1227.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1227.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1227.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub94.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellp